The page has been **stuck at q=0.894 for ~2 hours** because every post-19:40-KST tick has section_rewrite-failed. Root cause: AstroSage-70B keep_alive + 120s timeout (see §3.1). Fix shipped.

---

## 2. The judge-framing artifact (the biggest finding)

Before designing a quality push, I have to flag a measurement problem. **Δq metrics today overstate real improvement.**

Audit on the last 7 commits (page_id=57, decision='commit'):

| run | u0_median | u1_median | gap |
|---:|---:|---:|---:|
| 34 | 5.4545 | 9.0909 | +3.636 |
| 30 | 5.4545 | 9.0909 | +3.636 |
| 28 | 5.4545 | 9.0909 | +3.636 |
| 15 | 5.4545 | 9.0909 | +3.636 |
| 14 | 5.4545 | 9.0909 | +3.636 |
| 13 | 5.4545 | 9.0909 | +3.636 |
| 12 | 5.4545 | 9.0909 | +3.636 |

**u0=5.4545 and u1=9.0909 on every single tick.** That's not measurement variance — it's deterministic. The judge sees the baseline state and assigns rubric `{findings_clarity:2, open_questions_q:1, evidence_depth:2, frontier_signal:0, noise_penalty:-1}` → raw sum 4 → normalized 5.45. The candidate state gets `{findings_clarity:3, open_questions_q:2, evidence_depth:2, frontier_signal:1, noise_penalty:0}` → raw sum 8 → normalized 9.09.

The 5 parallel calls of deepseek-r1:14b at temp=0 return **byte-for-byte identical rubric JSON** for both u0 and u1. So `N=5` ensembling adds zero variance reduction; it's 5× compute for the same answer.

Two pathologies on top of that:

**Pathology A: judge framing leakage.** The same page content is rated 5.45 as baseline and 9.09 as candidate. Looking at the rationales:

- u0 rationale: `"…provides specific established results with numbers and mechanisms but lacks some clarity. Open questions are listed without depth. Evidence is cited well, but frontier mentions lack specificity. A noise penalty is applied due to repetitive content."`
- u1 rationale: `"…clearly presents established findings with specific details and citations, making it highly informative. It identifies open questions but could provide more depth on competing positions. Evidence is well-supported with recent citations. Frontier instruments are mentioned effectively. No noise penalties were applied."`

These describe **the same page** (the proposal in run 34 was a single-section rewrite — most content was unchanged). The 14B judge can't reliably distinguish baseline vs. candidate without prompt-level cues, so it pattern-matches to which framing it's currently in. The 0.24-per-tick Δq is mostly framing artifact.

**Pathology B: rubric is uncalibrated.** Five integer dimensions summing to a range of [-2, 12], normalized to [0, 10] by `(raw+2)*10/11`. Every committed tick scores exactly 8/12 raw on u1 → 9.09 normalized. The rubric never produces 9 or 10 because that would require `findings_clarity ≥ 2` AND `open_questions_q = 3` AND `evidence_depth = 2` AND `frontier_signal = 1` AND `noise_penalty = 0`. The 14B judge clamps at `open_questions_q ≤ 2` because the prompt rubric says open_questions_q=3 means "comprehensive coverage with named competing positions" — galaxy-evolution doesn't have a single section that names debate positions explicitly enough to earn 3.

**Implication for the roadmap:** to actually push **measured** q toward 0.95, two of the four items below must address the judge directly. Increasing the page's real quality without fixing the judge will look like a flat trajectory in autowiki_runs even if the page genuinely improves.

---

## 3. Roadmap (P0 → P3, ranked by Tori-day per q-point)

### P0 — Unblock the section_rewrite path (SHIPPED 2026-05-12 20:55 KST)

| Change | File | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `_call_astrosage` payload now sends `"keep_alive": "1h"` | `backend/app/agent_loop/autowiki/proposers.py:132` | Default 5-min keep_alive + 15-min tick interval = AstroSage cold-start every tick |
| `propose_section_rewrite` timeout 120s → 240s | `proposers.py:432` | Tori's prompt hardening at 19:40 KST raised required output to 400+ words; AstroSage-70B at ~30-50 tok/s needs 30-60s warm + cold-start headroom |

**Verification:** smoke test on the "Overview & Historical Framework" section returned 4792c / 688 words in 117.7s, with inline citations (Madau & Dickinson 2014; Stark et al. 2009; Labbé et al. 2023; Boylan-Kolchin 2023), quantitative facts (z∼2, 50% of stellar mass, 10-100 M⊙/yr, 10¹¹ M⊙ at z∼10-12), and zero banned phrases. Tori's hardened prompt is doing exactly what it should, once given enough time.

### P1 — Fix the judge variance + framing bias (1.5 day Tori)

The single highest-leverage change. Without this, real improvements won't register and false improvements will be rewarded.

**P1.a — Move judge to temp=0.1 + drop N=5 to N=3.** At temp=0, deepseek-r1:14b returns identical outputs across 5 parallel calls. N=5 is wasted compute. At temp=0.1 with N=3, the median absorbs single-call outliers without 5× the cost.

**P1.b — Anonymize judge framing.** The current judge prompt receives the page as a single block. We don't know yet whether the judge is being told "this is the baseline" vs. "this is the candidate" implicitly — but the byte-identical 5.45/9.09 split suggests yes. Concrete fix: pass the page through `_load_prompt()` with no "before/after" label, present it as the only content, and never expose the proposal_type to the judge.

**P1.c — Raise the rubric ceiling.** The current rubric tops out at 8/12 = 9.09 normalized because no real page hits all five dimensions at max. Either redefine the dimensions so that 12/12 is achievable, or normalize differently (e.g., percentile-based against the cohort of judged pages). My recommendation: redefine `open_questions_q` so that 3 = "lists ≥3 active debates with named positions" — a measurable target rather than "comprehensive coverage" which is vague.

**P1.d — Add a per-section sub-rubric.** Right now the judge sees the whole 27,478-char page and assigns one rubric. The Δq signal is dominated by which section happened to be rewritten. Split the rubric to score each of the 10 sections separately, then aggregate. The proposer's section_rewrite Δq will then localize to that section instead of being washed out.

Expected impact: post-P1, the Δq distribution should *narrow* (less of the 0.24 framing artifact) but *meaningful* commits will register as real progress.

### P2 — Add the 3 missing subtopics (0.5 day Tori, 4-6 days arXiv ingest)

`compute_health_score` returns `missing_subtopics: ['scaling_relations', 'color_bimodality', 'size_growth']`. Each missing subtopic is a `depth` penalty (current depth=0.7, target ≥0.9).

Recommendation:

| Subtopic | Section it belongs in | Suggested anchor papers (Kun to verify on ADS) |
|---|---|---|
| scaling_relations | Physical Mechanisms | Tully-Fisher (Tully & Fisher 1977), Faber-Jackson (Faber & Jackson 1976), fundamental plane (Djorgovski & Davis 1987), modern ALMA-resolved updates 2023-2025 |
| color_bimodality | Star Formation & Quenching | Baldry et al. 2004 (SDSS red sequence/blue cloud), green valley papers, Quench-time models post-2020 |
| size_growth | Observational Evidence | van Dokkum et al. 2010 (compact-quiescent at z~2), JWST size measurements 2023-2025, dry-merger scenarios |

Path of least resistance: `propose_claim_insert(claim_type="established")` for each subtopic, triggered when `depth < 0.7 and missing_subtopics`. Currently `depth=0.7` is exactly on the boundary — one claim insertion in the wrong section can flip it both ways. Set the boundary to `depth < 0.75` so the proposer reliably picks `claim_insert_subtopic` for the next few ticks.

### P3 — Pre-stage 2024+ arXiv papers (0.5 day Tori)

Live audit: **169 ArxivPaper rows in `astro-ph.GA` from 2024-2026**, of which only 73 evidence rows for galaxy-evolution come from that era. ~96 untapped recent papers, many of them JWST and DESI follow-ups directly relevant to size_growth, color_bimodality, and high-z evolution.

Action:

1. Run a one-shot SQL: `SELECT * FROM arxiv_papers WHERE category='astro-ph.GA' AND submitted >= '2024-01-01' AND id NOT IN (SELECT arxiv_paper_id FROM ... where claim.page_id=57)`. (Schema may not have arxiv_paper_id back-ref; substitute with arxiv_id matching against `evidence.arxiv_id` for claims of page 57.)
2. For each, run `classify_match_type(paper, db)` and if it lands `claim_evidence` for a galaxy-evolution claim, invoke `handle_claim_evidence` with this morning's fix (`arxiv_ingest.py:140`). Each successful insert bumps `freshness` toward 1.0 and `evidence_depth` per-claim.
3. The freshness threshold for evidence_link auto-firing is `freshness < 0.6` (proposer-picker logic at `autowiki/tasks.py:227`). Currently `freshness=0.608` so the proposer-picker will NOT pick evidence_link. After pre-staging, freshness should go to ~0.85+ and stay above 0.6 — meaning evidence_link auto-fires won't happen anymore from beat. That's fine: P2's claim_insert_subtopic will be the new auto-pick path.

**Caveat:** v1.1 of `arxiv_wiki_feed_design_v1.md` §v1.1-N3 documents that `handle_page_extension` has a separate bug (`_chat_parallel` signature mismatch). That's not blocking for P3 — `handle_claim_evidence` was the path I fixed today.

### P4 — Section-rewrite cycle through all 10 sections (0.5 day Tori)

Current proposer-picker logic always picks the FIRST `## section` it finds (`autowiki/tasks.py:264-267`), which is "Overview & Historical Framework". Every section_rewrite has rewritten that single section. The other 9 sections never see a rewrite proposal.

Fix: at `tasks.py:264`, replace the regex pick with a round-robin (track last-rewritten section in `wiki_pages.last_renovated_section`, or in a new column, or in Redis). Then a tick at q=0.89 picks the section that hasn't been rewritten longest. Within ~10 ticks the page rotates through every section.

### P5 — Reduce VOTE_THRESHOLD for new debate claims (DEFERRED, see open questions)

Currently `claim_insert_debate` triggers when `debate_count < 4` (proposer-picker logic). The page has 4 debate claims already, so this path won't fire. Should we raise the target to 6-8 debate claims? Debate claims are the rubric's `open_questions_q` driver — more debate claims = higher rubric ceiling, especially after P1.c's redefinition.

---

## 4. Projected trajectory

Assumptions: P0 lands tonight (done), P1 lands by 2026-05-15, P2-P3 by 2026-05-17, P4 by 2026-05-18. All numbers below are the *measured* q (after P1 calibration fix).

| Date | Expected q | Driver |
|---|---:|---|
| 2026-05-12 23:00 | 0.894 | P0 fix lands, section_rewrite cycle resumes (currently always rewriting Overview, capped at 0.894 because u1=9.09 is the rubric ceiling) |
| 2026-05-13 | 0.894 | (no movement until P1 fixes the ceiling) |
| 2026-05-15 | **0.91-0.93** | P1 deploys, judge ceiling raised, real rubric variance now visible, claim_insert_subtopic picks scaling_relations subtopic |
| 2026-05-16 | **0.93-0.95** | P2 lands all 3 subtopics, depth → 0.9+, freshness keeps climbing |
| 2026-05-17 | **0.94-0.96** | P3 pre-stage drops fresh evidence into existing claims, frontier_signal in rubric improves |
| 2026-05-18 | **≥ 0.95** target | P4 round-robin section rewrites cover the 9 untouched sections; cumulative content quality rises |

**The 0.95 target is reachable but contingent on P1 (judge calibration). Without P1, q stays at 0.894 indefinitely no matter how good the content gets.**

